bug.short_desc: Make use of CSS classes as often as possible

long_desc.thetext: Currently, the style tag is used to apply CSS styles to DOM elements. Setting a CSS class instead of single styles (very bad!) or a string of styles is slower than setting a CSS class. So the idea is to take advantage of these behavior and use CSS classes as often as possible in the framework.
Created attachment 727 Test case to see the times for each style change.

The tests change 10000 times the style. 1. with the usage of a class 2. by setting every style in a single line like div.style[name] = value 3. by setting all styles inline at once
Times tested with different browsers on my MacMini:
Safari 4 Class changes: 1ms (56ms) single style changes: 281ms (21ms) insline style changes: 5ms (13ms)
Firefox 3.6 Class changes: 3ms (13ms) single style changes: 2588ms (32ms) insline style changes: 2ms (27ms)
Firefox 3.0 Class changes: 3ms (25ms) single style changes: 817ms (10ms) insline style changes: 3ms (30ms)
Chrome 5 Class changes: 0ms (19ms) single style changes: 433ms (17ms) insline style changes: 8ms (85ms)
Opera 10 Class changes: 9ms (2ms) single style changes: 339ms (1ms) insline style changes: 9ms (1ms)
Created attachment 733 Used test HTML file.

IE 8 Class changes: 46ms (16ms) single style changes: 1062ms (16ms) insline style changes: 47ms (31ms)
The value in brackets are the rendering times.
If my tests are correct, there seems to be not a huge difference between setting a class and setting the styles as one sting inline. But setting the styles one by one is expensive!
Created attachment 735 Results of the measurements.

After checking the current implementation of qooxdoo, it seems that if it is possible, we set the styles as one single string, which is as fast as setting a class in most browsers. If thats not possible because we don't want to override the current styles, we have to set the styles one by one. But setting the styles one by one is better than getting the styles and parsing them for further processing. So I think the performance potential in here is not that big as we thought. --> WONTFIX
Closed all bugs already shipped with a release.
